To illustrate the described scenario using TikZ in LaTeX, we can create a diagram that represents the spacetime region, the expanding region, and the hypersurfaces involved. Below is a sample TikZ code that captures the essence of your description:

```latex
\documentclass[tikz,border=3mm]{standalone}
\usetikzlibrary{calc,arrows.meta}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.5]
    % Draw the time axis
    \draw[->] (0,-2) -- (0,4) node[above]{$t$};

    % Draw the radial coordinate axis
    \draw[->] (-4,0) -- (4,0) node[right]{$r$};

    % Draw the expanding region
    \draw[dashed, thick] (0,0) ellipse (3 and 2);

    % Label the expanding region
    \node at (3.5,2.5) {$\text{Expanding Region}$};

    % Draw the initial hypersurface Σ_r0
    \draw[dotted, thick] (0,0) circle (1);

    % Label the initial hypersurface
    \node at (1,1) {$\Sigma_{r_0}$};

    % Draw the Cauchy surface Σ_C
    \draw[dashed, thick] (0,0) circle (2);

    % Label the Cauchy surface
    \node at (2,2) {$\Sigma_{\mathcal{C}}$};

    % Draw the limit as R approaches infinity
    \draw[thick, ->] (3.5,2.5) -- (4.5,2.5) node[midway, above]{$\lim_{R \to \infty} \psi_R$};

    % Add labels for the regions
    \node at (0,-2.5) {$\text{Initial Condition Region}$};
    \node at (0,4.5) {$\text{Asymptotic Region}$};
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```

